  // =============================================================================
  // ANTIARRHYTHMICS
  // =============================================================================
  {
    id: 'antiarrhythmics',
    subjectId: 'pharmacology',
    subspecialtyId: 'pharmacology-cvs',
    name: 'Antiarrhythmics',
    slug: 'antiarrhythmics',
    description: 'Vaughan-Williams classification, Class I-IV, mechanisms, uses',
    content: {
      concept: `# Antiarrhythmic Drugs

## Vaughan-Williams Classification

| Class | Mechanism | Subclass | Examples |
|-------|-----------|----------|----------|
| **I** | Na⁺ channel blockers | Ia, Ib, Ic | Below |
| **II** | β-blockers | - | Metoprolol, Esmolol |
| **III** | K⁺ channel blockers | - | Amiodarone, Sotalol, Dofetilide |
| **IV** | Ca²⁺ channel blockers | - | Verapamil, Diltiazem |
| **Others** | Miscellaneous | - | Adenosine, Digoxin, Mg²⁺ |

---

## CLASS I: SODIUM CHANNEL BLOCKERS

### Subclassification
| Subclass | Effect on AP | Kinetics | Drugs |
|----------|--------------|----------|-------|
| **Ia** | ↑ Duration | Intermediate | Quinidine, Procainamide, Disopyramide |
| **Ib** | ↓ Duration | Fast | Lidocaine, Mexiletine, Phenytoin |
| **Ic** | No change | Slow | Flecainide, Propafenone |

### Class Ia: "Intermediate Kinetics"

**Quinidine**
\`\`\`
Na⁺ block + K⁺ block → ↑ APD, ↑ ERP
                     → Prolongs QT interval
\`\`\`
- Uses: AF, WPW with AF
- ADRs: 
  - **Torsades de Pointes** (proarrhythmic!)
  - Cinchonism (tinnitus, headache, nausea)
  - Diarrhea (30%)
  - Thrombocytopenia
  - Anticholinergic effects

**Procainamide**
- IV use for wide-complex tachycardia
- ADRs:
  - **Drug-induced lupus** (30-50% develop ANA, 10-20% clinical lupus)
  - Agranulocytosis
  - Hypotension (IV)

**Disopyramide**
- Strongest **negative inotrope** of Class Ia
- Strong anticholinergic effects
- Use: HCM with obstruction (↓ contractility helps)
- ADRs: Urinary retention, dry mouth, constipation

### Class Ib: "Fast Kinetics"

**Lidocaine**
\`\`\`
Blocks Na⁺ channels in depolarized tissue
Preferentially binds to inactivated channels
→ More effective in ischemic tissue
\`\`\`
- Uses: Ventricular arrhythmias (VT, VF)
- IV only (high first-pass metabolism)
- ADRs: CNS toxicity (seizures, confusion), bradycardia
- Relatively safe in ischemia (does NOT prolong QT)

**Mexiletine**
- Oral analogue of lidocaine
- Used for ventricular arrhythmias, neuropathic pain

### Class Ic: "Slow Kinetics"

**Flecainide**
- Potent Na⁺ channel block
- Uses: SVT, AF in structurally normal hearts
- **CONTRAINDICATED post-MI** (CAST trial: ↑ mortality)
- Also blocks K⁺ channels (some)

**Propafenone**
- Na⁺ block + weak β-block + Ca²⁺ block
- Uses: AF, SVT
- Tastes metallic
- Same contraindication in structural heart disease

> 💎 **High Yield**: Class Ic drugs are CONTRAINDICATED in structural heart disease and ischemia (proarrhythmic risk per CAST trial)

---

## CLASS II: BETA-BLOCKERS

### Mechanism
\`\`\`
β1 blockade →
  ↓ cAMP →
  ↓ If current (automaticity) →
  ↓ Ca²⁺ influx →
  ↓ HR, ↓ AV conduction
\`\`\`

### Drugs
- **Metoprolol, Atenolol** - Oral, long-term use
- **Esmolol** - IV, ultra-short acting (t½ = 9 min)
- **Propranolol** - Non-selective, multiple uses

### Uses
- Rate control in AF, atrial flutter
- AVNRT, AVRT
- Post-MI arrhythmia prophylaxis
- Catecholaminergic polymorphic VT

---

## CLASS III: POTASSIUM CHANNEL BLOCKERS

### Mechanism
Block K⁺ channels → ↑ APD, ↑ ERP → Prolongs QT

### Amiodarone - "The Kitchen Sink"

**Multiple Mechanisms:**
\`\`\`
- K⁺ channel block (Class III)
- Na⁺ channel block (Class I)
- Ca²⁺ channel block (Class IV)
- β-blocker effect (Class II)
- Anti-thyroid effect (contains iodine)
\`\`\`

**Pharmacokinetics:**
- Extremely lipophilic
- Half-life: **40-55 DAYS**
- Loading required (weeks to reach steady state)
- Minimal negative inotropy (safe in HF)

**Uses:**
- **Most effective antiarrhythmic**
- AF, atrial flutter
- VT, VF
- WPW with AF
- Safe in heart failure

**Adverse Effects (extensive):**
| System | Effect | Monitoring |
|--------|--------|------------|
| **Thyroid** | Hypo- (more common) or Hyperthyroidism | TFTs q6 months |
| **Pulmonary** | Fibrosis (fatal!) | CXR, PFTs yearly |
| **Hepatic** | Transaminitis, cirrhosis | LFTs |
| **Cornea** | Deposits (>90%), optic neuritis | Ophthalmology |
| **Skin** | Blue-gray discoloration, photosensitivity | Sun protection |
| **Cardiac** | Bradycardia, ↑ QT (Torsades rare) | ECG |
| **Neurologic** | Tremor, ataxia, neuropathy | Clinical |

> 💎 **High Yield**: "Amiodarone touches every organ" - Baseline TFTs, LFTs, PFTs, CXR, eye exam before starting

### Sotalol
- Non-selective β-blocker + Class III
- Uses: AF, VT
- ADR: Torsades de Pointes (dose-dependent)
- Renally excreted (adjust in CKD)

### Dofetilide
- Pure K⁺ channel (IKr) blocker
- Uses: AF/atrial flutter cardioversion/maintenance
- Must be initiated in hospital (Torsades risk)

### Ibutilide
- IV only, acute AF/flutter cardioversion
- High Torsades risk (8%)
- Must monitor for 4-6 hours post-infusion

---

## CLASS IV: CALCIUM CHANNEL BLOCKERS

### Drugs
- **Verapamil**
- **Diltiazem**

### Mechanism
Block L-type Ca²⁺ channels in SA and AV node
→ ↓ Automaticity, ↓ AV conduction, ↑ AV nodal ERP

### Uses
- Rate control in AF
- AVNRT, AVRT (terminate)
- Rate control in MAT
- **CONTRAINDICATED** in WPW with AF (accelerates bypass tract)

---

## OTHER AGENTS

### Adenosine
**Mechanism:** A1 receptor → ↑ K⁺ efflux → Hyperpolarization → AV block

**Pharmacokinetics:**
- Half-life: < 10 seconds
- Must give rapid IV push with flush

**Uses:**
- **First-line for stable narrow-complex SVT (AVNRT/AVRT)**
- Diagnostic in wide-complex tachycardia

**ADRs:**
- Transient: Flushing, chest pain, dyspnea, bronchospasm
- Effect blocked by methylxanthines (caffeine, theophylline)
- Effect enhanced by dipyridamole

### Digoxin
- Vagotonic (↑ ACh at AV node)
- Uses: Rate control in AF (especially with HF)
- Narrow therapeutic index

### Magnesium Sulfate
- First-line for Torsades de Pointes
- Also useful in digoxin toxicity

---

## ARRHYTHMIA-SPECIFIC THERAPY

| Arrhythmia | First-Line | Alternatives |
|------------|-----------|--------------|
| AF rate control | β-blocker or non-DHP CCB | Digoxin (with HF) |
| AF rhythm control | Flecainide (no HF), Amiodarone (with HF) | Sotalol, Dofetilide |
| AVNRT/AVRT | Adenosine (acute), β-blocker/CCB (chronic) | Ablation |
| WPW + AF | Procainamide, Ibutilide | Amiodarone |
| VT/VF | Amiodarone, Lidocaine | β-blocker |
| Torsades | IV Magnesium | Isoproterenol, overdrive pacing |
| Digoxin toxicity | DigiFab | Atropine, Mg, phenytoin |`,
      keyPoints: [
        'Class I: Na⁺ block (Ia ↑ APD, Ib ↓ APD, Ic no change)',
        'Class Ic CONTRAINDICATED in structural heart disease (CAST trial)',
        'Amiodarone: Multiple mechanisms, t½ 40-55 days, extensive toxicity (thyroid, lung, liver, eyes)',
        'Adenosine: First-line for AVNRT/AVRT, t½ <10 sec, blocked by caffeine',
        'WPW with AF: Avoid AV nodal blockers (digoxin, verapamil, adenosine) - use procainamide/amiodarone',
        'Torsades de Pointes: IV Magnesium first-line',
        'Sotalol, Dofetilide: Pure Class III, high Torsades risk'
      ],
      examPrep: {
        summary: `**Antiarrhythmics - Quick Review**

🔹 **Class I** (Na⁺ block):
- Ia: ↑ APD (Quinidine - Torsades, Procainamide - lupus)
- Ib: ↓ APD (Lidocaine - VT, safe in ischemia)
- Ic: Flecainide - CONTRAINDICATED post-MI

🔹 **Class II** (β-blockers): Rate control, esmolol ultra-short

🔹 **Class III** (K⁺ block): 
- Amiodarone: Most effective, t½ 40-55 days, thyroid/lung/liver toxicity
- Sotalol: β-blocker + Class III

🔹 **Class IV** (Ca²⁺ block): Verapamil/Diltiazem - AV nodal effects

🔹 **Others**: Adenosine (SVT), Digoxin (AF+HF), Mg (Torsades)`,
        mnemonics: [
          'Class Ia drugs: "Queens Prefer Disco" - Quinidine, Procainamide, Disopyramide',
          'Class Ib drugs: "Lame, Mex, Phen" - Lidocaine, Mexiletine, Phenytoin',
          'Amiodarone toxicity: "CHECK Lips" - Cornea, Hepatic, Endocrine (thyroid), Cardiac, Skin (photosensitivity, blue), Lungs, Neurologic',
