    name: 'Heart Failure Drugs',
    slug: 'heart-failure-drugs',
    description: 'ACE inhibitors, beta-blockers, digoxin, ARNI, SGLT2i',
    content: {
      concept: `# Heart Failure Pharmacotherapy

## Overview

Heart failure treatment has evolved from symptom control to disease-modifying therapy. Modern treatment targets neurohormonal activation.

## HFrEF vs HFpEF

| Parameter | HFrEF | HFpEF |
|-----------|-------|-------|
| EF | ≤40% | ≥50% |
| Primary pathology | Systolic dysfunction | Diastolic dysfunction |
| Drug evidence | Strong | Limited |

---

## QUADRUPLE THERAPY FOR HFrEF (GDMT)

\`\`\`
Modern HFrEF Treatment: "Fantastic Four"

1. ACEi/ARB/ARNI
2. β-blocker (specific ones only!)
3. MRA (Spironolactone/Eplerenone)
4. SGLT2 inhibitor

Each reduces mortality independently!
\`\`\`

---

## ACE INHIBITORS / ARBs IN HF

### Evidence
- **CONSENSUS** (1987): Enalapril ↓ mortality in severe HF
- **SOLVD** (1991): Enalapril ↓ mortality and hospitalizations

### Mechanism in HF
\`\`\`
HF → ↑ RAAS activation → Vasoconstriction, Na⁺ retention, remodeling

ACEi blocks:
  ↓ Ang II → Vasodilation, ↓ afterload
  ↓ Aldosterone → ↓ Na⁺ retention, ↓ K⁺ loss
  ↑ Bradykinin → Vasodilation
  ↓ Remodeling → Prevents progression
\`\`\`

### Key Points
- Start LOW, go SLOW (avoid hypotension)
- Target highest tolerated dose
- Up to 30% creatinine rise acceptable
- Monitor K⁺

---

## ANGIOTENSIN RECEPTOR-NEPRILYSIN INHIBITOR (ARNI)

### Sacubitril/Valsartan (Entresto)

**Mechanism:**
\`\`\`
Sacubitril → Inhibits neprilysin → ↑ Natriuretic peptides (ANP, BNP)
                                 → ↑ Bradykinin
                                 → Vasodilation, natriuresis, ↓ remodeling

Valsartan → Blocks AT1 receptor → ↓ Ang II effects
\`\`\`

**Evidence: PARADIGM-HF Trial**
- ARNI vs Enalapril in HFrEF
- 20% ↓ CV death or HF hospitalization
- 16% ↓ All-cause mortality
- Now preferred over ACEi/ARB if tolerated

**Key Points:**
- Wait 36 hours after stopping ACEi (angioedema risk)
- Can't give with ACEi
- Causes hypotension (start low dose)
- ↑ BNP but ↓ NT-proBNP (neprilysin effect)

---

## BETA-BLOCKERS IN HF

### Paradox Explained
\`\`\`
Acute HF: β-blockers harmful (↓ contractility)
Chronic HF: β-blockers LIFE-SAVING

Why? Chronic sympathetic activation is TOXIC:
  - Myocyte apoptosis
  - Arrhythmias
  - Remodeling
  
β-blockers block this → ↑ Survival
\`\`\`

### Approved Agents (ONLY these have mortality data!)
| Drug | Key Trial | Notes |
|------|-----------|-------|
| **Carvedilol** | COPERNICUS, CAPRICORN | α1 + β block, best in NYHA III-IV |
| **Bisoprolol** | CIBIS-II | β1-selective |
| **Metoprolol succinate** | MERIT-HF | β1-selective, NOT tartrate |

> 💎 **High Yield**: Metoprolol TARTRATE does NOT have mortality benefit in HF. Only SUCCINATE (extended-release) works.

### Initiation
- Start LOW (1/10th target dose)
- Increase every 2 weeks
- Expect temporary worsening initially
- Don't start in decompensated HF

---

## MINERALOCORTICOID RECEPTOR ANTAGONISTS (MRA)

### Spironolactone

**Evidence: RALES Trial**
- Added to standard therapy (ACEi, diuretic, digoxin)
- 30% ↓ Mortality
- 35% ↓ Hospitalizations

**Mechanism:**
\`\`\`
Aldosterone causes:
  - Na⁺ retention, K⁺ loss
  - Myocardial fibrosis
  - Endothelial dysfunction
  - Arrhythmias

Spironolactone blocks all these
\`\`\`

**ADRs:**
- Hyperkalemia (especially with ACEi)
- **Gynecomastia** (17% - antiandrogen effect)
- Menstrual irregularities

### Eplerenone
- Selective MR antagonist
- **EPHESUS**: ↓ Mortality post-MI with LV dysfunction
- Less gynecomastia (1-2%)
- More expensive

---

## SGLT2 INHIBITORS

### Drugs
- **Dapagliflozin** (DAPA-HF)
- **Empagliflozin** (EMPEROR-Reduced)

**Mechanism in HF (not fully understood):**
\`\`\`
- Osmotic diuresis, natriuresis
- ↓ Preload, ↓ afterload
- ↑ Ketone utilization (efficient fuel)
- ↓ Cardiac remodeling
- ↓ Inflammation, oxidative stress
\`\`\`

**Evidence:**
- DAPA-HF: 26% ↓ CV death or HF worsening
- Works equally in diabetics AND non-diabetics!

**Key Points:**
- Now part of quadruple therapy
- Works in HFrEF AND HFpEF (EMPEROR-Preserved, DELIVER)
- ADRs: UTI, genital mycotic infections, euglycemic DKA
- Avoid if eGFR <20

---

## DIURETICS IN HF

### Loop Diuretics
- **Symptomatic relief** (congestion)
- NO mortality benefit
- Furosemide, bumetanide, torsemide

### Thiazides
- Add for diuretic resistance
- Metolazone + Furosemide (synergistic)

> 💎 **High Yield**: Diuretics improve symptoms but NOT survival in HF

---

## DIGOXIN

### Mechanism
\`\`\`
Inhibits Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase →
  ↑ Intracellular Na⁺ →
  ↓ Na⁺/Ca²⁺ exchange →
  ↑ Intracellular Ca²⁺ →
  ↑ Contractility (positive inotropy)

Also: ↑ Vagal tone → ↓ HR, ↓ AV conduction
\`\`\`

### Evidence: DIG Trial
- No mortality benefit
- ↓ Hospitalizations
- Narrow therapeutic window

### Indications
- HFrEF with persistent symptoms despite GDMT
- AF rate control in HF

### Toxicity
**Risk factors:** Hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia, renal failure, elderly

**Signs:**
- GI: Nausea, vomiting, anorexia
- CNS: Confusion, visual changes (yellow-green halos)
- Cardiac: Any arrhythmia! (classically: accelerated junctional rhythm, bidirectional VT)

**Treatment:** DigiFab (digoxin-specific antibody fragments)

---

## HYDRALAZINE + ISDN (H-ISDN)

### Mechanism
- Hydralazine: Arteriolar vasodilation (↓ afterload)
- ISDN: Venodilation (↓ preload)

### Evidence: A-HeFT
- Added benefit in African Americans with HFrEF
- 43% ↓ Mortality

### Use
- Alternative when ACEi/ARB not tolerated
- Add-on in African American patients

---

## IVABRADINE

### Mechanism
Blocks If (funny) channel in SA node → ↓ HR only

### Evidence: SHIFT Trial
- ↓ HF hospitalization
- HR must be >70 bpm and in sinus rhythm
- No mortality benefit

### Use
- Add-on when HR remains >70 despite max β-blocker
- Must be in sinus rhythm

---

## TREATMENT ALGORITHM

\`\`\`
HFrEF (EF ≤40%):

Step 1: Start all 4 classes
        - ARNI (or ACEi/ARB)
        - β-blocker (carvedilol/bisoprolol/metoprolol succinate)
        - MRA (spironolactone/eplerenone)
        - SGLT2i (dapagliflozin/empagliflozin)

Step 2: Titrate to target doses

Step 3: Add-on therapy if symptomatic
        - Loop diuretic (for congestion)
        - Digoxin (symptoms + AF)
        - Ivabradine (HR >70 in sinus)
        - H-ISDN (African Americans or ACEi intolerant)
        - Device: ICD/CRT if indicated
\`\`\``,
      keyPoints: [
        'Quadruple therapy: ARNI/ACEi + β-blocker + MRA + SGLT2i (all reduce mortality)',
        'ARNI (sacubitril/valsartan): Superior to ACEi per PARADIGM-HF; 36-hour washout from ACEi',
        'Only 3 β-blockers proven in HF: Carvedilol, Bisoprolol, Metoprolol SUCCINATE',
        'Spironolactone: RALES trial, 30% ↓ mortality, causes gynecomastia',
